# 🚀 Day 46/90 – Designing the OCR + AI Processing Pipeline

Welcome to **Day 46!** 🎉

Today we'll design the **most important feature** of your Blood Report Analyzer.

Without this feature, your app is just a file storage app.

With this feature, it becomes an **AI-powered health assistant**.

Today's question is:

> **"What happens from the moment a user uploads a blood report until they receive an easy-to-understand explanation?"**

This entire journey is called the **OCR + AI Processing Pipeline**.

---

# 🎯 Today's Goal

By the end of today, you'll understand:

* How a PDF becomes text
* How text becomes structured blood values
* How users correct OCR mistakes
* How AI generates explanations
* How everything is stored

This is the heart of your product.

---

# The Complete Pipeline

```text
User Uploads Report
          │
          ▼
Store Original PDF
          │
          ▼
OCR Extracts Text
          │
          ▼
Find Blood Test Values
          │
          ▼
User Reviews & Corrects
          │
          ▼
Save Final Values
          │
          ▼
Generate AI Summary
          │
          ▼
Save Everything
          │
          ▼
Show Results
```

---

# Step 1 – User Uploads Report

The user chooses:

* PDF
* Camera
* Gallery

Example:

```
Apollo_Report_July2026.pdf
```

The app uploads it to your backend.

---

# Step 2 – Store the Original Report

**Don't process the report first.**

First, save the original PDF securely.

Example:

```
Storage

↓

User123

↓

Report001.pdf
```

Why?

Because if OCR fails, you still have the original file.

---

# Step 3 – OCR Reads the Report

OCR (Optical Character Recognition) converts the report into plain text.

Example:

Report contains:

```
Hemoglobin .......... 13.2 g/dL

HbA1c ............... 5.8 %

Vitamin D ........... 18 ng/mL
```

OCR converts this into digital text.

---

# Step 4 – Extract Blood Test Values

OCR gives a lot of text.

Your backend now finds only the important tests.

Example:

Instead of saving everything,

save:

```json
{
  "Hemoglobin": 13.2,
  "HbA1c": 5.8,
  "Vitamin D": 18
}
```

This is called **structured data**.

---

# Step 5 – Match Different Lab Formats

Different laboratories use different names.

Example:

Apollo

```
Hemoglobin
```

Another lab

```
Hb
```

Another lab

```
Haemoglobin
```

All of these should become:

```
Hemoglobin
```

This process is called **normalization**.

---

# Step 6 – User Reviews OCR

Never assume OCR is perfect.

Show the extracted values.

```
Hemoglobin

13.2

✏ Edit
```

If OCR mistakenly reads:

```
18
```

instead of

```
13

```

the user can correct it.

This is why the OCR Review screen is so important.

---

# Step 7 – Save the Corrected Values

Only after the user taps **Confirm** do we save:

```
Hemoglobin = 13.2

HbA1c = 5.8

Vitamin D = 18
```

These become the official values for that report.

---

# Step 8 – Send Data to AI

Notice something important.

We do **not** send the PDF to AI.

We send the structured values.

Example:

```json
{
  "Age": 35,
  "Gender": "Male",
  "Hemoglobin": 13.2,
  "HbA1c": 5.8,
  "Vitamin D": 18
}
```

This is faster, cheaper, and more reliable.

---

# Step 9 – AI Generates an Explanation

The AI returns something like:

```
Your hemoglobin is within the reference range shown on your report.

Your Vitamin D appears below the reference range.

Your HbA1c appears within the normal range shown on your report.

These explanations are informational and should not replace advice from a healthcare professional.
```

Notice:

* Simple language
* No diagnosis
* No unnecessary medical jargon

---

# Step 10 – Save Everything

For every uploaded report, store:

```
Original PDF

↓

Extracted Text

↓

Corrected Blood Values

↓

AI Summary

↓

Upload Date

↓

Hospital Name
```

Nothing should be overwritten.

Every report becomes part of the user's health history.

---

# Step 11 – Display Results

Now show the user:

```
Report Summary

Hemoglobin

13.2

Normal

----------------

Vitamin D

18

Below reference range

----------------

HbA1c

5.8

Within reference range

----------------

AI Explanation
```

Everything on one screen.

---

# Handling OCR Failures

Sometimes OCR won't recognize a report.

Instead of showing an error like:

```
OCR Failed
```

Show something helpful:

```
We couldn't read some values.

Please review and enter the missing values manually.
```

This creates a much better user experience.

---

# Handling Missing Tests

Not every report contains every blood test.

For example:

```
Report A

Hemoglobin

HbA1c

Vitamin D
```

Another report:

```
Hemoglobin

Platelets

WBC
```

Your app should display only the tests that exist in that report.

Don't force empty fields.

